<Base
  title="CAST · Xiaochuan Li"
  description="From a modal state — a set of possible worlds plus a modal constraint — CAST projects controlled text in English, German, and Chinese, then grades whether a model tracks the world-set or the words."
  toc={true}
>
  <article class="prose">
    <div class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-2">
      Supporting workbench · modal compiler (formerly MiniCausalLang)
    </div>
    <h1>CAST — one modal state, many languages</h1>
    <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] italic !text-lg !mb-8">
      From a modal state, generate controlled language — then check the model tracks the surviving world-set, not the words.
    </p>

    <p>
      CAST starts from a <em>known modal state</em> — a candidate set of possible worlds
      <code>W = {"{w₁…w₄}"}</code> plus a ◇/□ constraint — runs the elimination, and
      <strong>projects the surviving world-set to controlled text</strong> in English, German, and
      Chinese ("cannot possibly be" / "kann unmöglich … sein" / "不可能是"). Correct behaviour is
      <em>indifference over exactly the survivors</em>, not picking one world. Because the logical
      content is fixed by construction, any cross-language difference must come from linguistic form,
      and structure recovery scores against a known target rather than a guess. This is the workbench
      the modal-concepts thesis runs on.
    </p>

    <p>
      The general machine is a <strong>compiler from a formal-semantic object to multilingual text</strong>;
      "evaluation" means checking the model's behaviour is isomorphic to the pre-compilation object.
      Its <strong>first domain is the causal graph</strong> (below) — the sandbox that made the
      certification cut decidable — and the modal-state compiler above is the general form. Minimal
      pairs are single-variable operations at the formal layer (swap a predicate for an extensionally
      identical fictional twin; add a retraction), and the surface is always regenerated, never
      hand-edited.
    </p>

    <MiniCausalFigure />

    <p>
      The hard direction in my <a href="/writing/inferential-productivity">note on inferential
      productivity</a> is reverse: given a behavior, what is the <em>smallest</em> causal structure
      that must be there? A real model usually offers no ground truth to score a recovered structure
      against. CAST keeps the bridge explicit before trusting the method elsewhere: specify the
      grammar, compile it into a causal graph, enumerate the inferences that graph licenses, train or
      evaluate a model on that data, and test whether behavioral recovery returns the planted
      structure.
    </p>

    <p>
      This is supporting infrastructure, not a paper in its own right. It makes the link between
      linguistic form and the formal-semantic structure it encodes — causal structure first, modal
      structure next — explicit enough to be falsifiable against a known answer.
    </p>

    <hr/>
    <p class="!text-sm !text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">An interactive workbench — specify a grammar, compile the graph, see what recovery returns — will live here.</p>
  </article>
</Base>
